{{Infobox Wrestling event |name=Rey de Reyes 2003 |image=LaParkaE3.jpg |caption=[[La Parka II|La Parka Jr.]] 2003 Rey de Reyes |promotion=[[Lucha Libre AAA World Wide|AAA]] |date=March 16, 2003<ref name="Rey2003">{{cite web | url = http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/mexico/aaa/rey.html#2003 | title = Asistencia Asesoria y Administracion Rey de Reyes Tournament| accessdate = February 19, 2009 | date= March 16, 2003| publisher= ProWrestlingHistory.com}}</ref> |venue= |city=[[Zapopan]], [[Jalisco]], [[Mexico]]<ref name="Rey2003"/> |attendance= |liveevent=Y |lastevent=[[Guerra de Titanes (2002)]] |nextevent=[[Triplemanía XI]] |event=[[Rey de Reyes]] |lastevent2=[[Rey de Reyes (2002)]] |nextevent2=[[Rey de Reyes (2004)]] }} The '''Rey de Reyes 2003''' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]] for "King of Kings") was the seventh annual [[Rey de Reyes]] [[professional wrestling]] tournament and show, produced by the Mexican [[wrestling promotion]] [[Lucha Libre AAA World Wide|AAA]]. The event took place on March 16, 2003 in [[Zapopan]], [[Jalisco]], [[Mexico]]. In a break from tradition that year's Rey de Reyes tournament featured six former Rey de Reyes winners wrestling each other to determine 2003's Rey de Reyes. The final match saw [[La Parka, Jr.]] compete against [[Abismo Negro]].
==Production== ===Background=== Starting in 1997 and every year since then the Mexican ''[[Lucha Libre]]'', or [[professional wrestling]], [[wrestling promotion|company]] [[Lucha Libre AAA World Wide|AAA]] has held a [[Rey de Reyes]] (Spanish for "King of Kings') show in the spring. The 1997 version was held in February,<ref name="Rey1997">{{cite web | url = http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/mexico/aaa/rey.html#1997 | title = Asistencia Asesoria y Administracion Rey de Reyes | accessdate = February 19, 2009 | date=February 21, 1997 | publisher= ProWrestlingHistory.com}}</ref> while all subsequent Rey de Reyes shows were held in March. As part of their annual Rey de Reyes event AAA holds the [[eponym]]ious Rey de Reyes tournament to determine that specific year's ''Rey''.<ref name=YIR1997>{{cite news|title=1997 Especial!|work=Box y Lucha Magazine|pages=2–28|id=issue 2332|date=January 7, 1998|language=Spanish}}</ref> Most years the show hosts both the qualifying round and the final match, but on occasion the qualifying matches have been held prior to the event as part of AAA's weekly television shows.<ref name=Lucha2004>{{cite news|title=Número Especial - Lo mejor de la mejor de la Lucha Libre Mexicana durante el 2004|work=SuperLuchas|id=Issue 91|date=January 24, 2005|language=Spanish}}</ref> The traditional format consists of four preliminary rounds, each a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|Four-man elimination match]] with each of the four winners face off in the tournament finals, again under elimination rules.<ref name="Rey1997"/> There have been years where AAA has employed a different format to determine a winner.<ref name=Lucha2004/> The winner of the Rey de Reyes tournament is given a large ornamental sword to symbolize their victory, but is normally not guaranteed any other rewards for winning the tournament, although some years becoming the Rey de Reyes has earned the winner a match for the [[AAA Mega Championship]]. From 1999 through 2009 AAA also held an annual ''[[AAA Reina de Reinas Championship|Reina de Reinas]]'' ("Queen of Queens") tournament, but later turned that into an actual championship that could be defended at any point during the year, abandoning the annual tournament concept.<ref name=Reinas1999>{{Cite book | author=Royal Duncan and Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories | publisher=Archeus Communications |chapter= Mexico: AAA Reina de Reinas | page= 400 | year= 2000 | isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref><ref name=Reinas12>{{cite news | author = SuperLuchas staff | title = Lo Mejor de la Lucha Libre Mexicana 2008 | work =SuperLuchas | id = issue 296 | date = January 6, 2008 | url=http://superluchas.net/?p=11145 | accessdate = July 11, 2009| language = Spanish}}</ref><ref name=Reinas13>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.net/2009/09/26/aaa-heroes-inmortales-homenaje-a-antonio-pena-resultados-en-vivo-26-septiembre-2009-%C2%BFque-pasara-con-la-lucha-entre-charly-manson-y-chessman-%C2%BFquien-sera-el-luchador-sorpresa/ | title= AAA- Héroes Inmortales III- (Resultados en vivo 26 septiembre 2009) – Cibernético gana el Trofeo Antonio Peña – Electroshock sustituye a Charly Manson contra Chessman – El luchador sorpresa fue Konan Big | author= Marquina, Alva | date= September 26, 2009 | accessdate= September 27, 2009 | publisher= ''SuperLuchas'' Magazine| language=Spanish}}</ref> The 2003 show was the seventh Rey de Reyes show in the series.
===Storylines=== The Rey de Reyes show featured at least four [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] with different wrestlers involved in pre-existing [[Screenplay|scripted]] feuds, [[plot (narrative)|plots]] and [[narrative thread|storylines]]. Wrestlers portray either [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heels]] (referred to as ''rudos'' in Mexico, those that portrayed the "bad guys") or [[Face (professional wrestling)|faces]] (''técnicos'' in Mexico, the "good guy" characters) as they followed a series of tension-building events, which culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches. Records for four of matches have been found for the 2003 Rey de Reyes show, but it is possible more took place.
