{{Infobox officeholder |name = Richard James Sheirer |image = |caption = |office = [[NYC Emergency Management|Director, NYC Office of Emergency Management]] |term_start = February, 2000 |term_end = March, 2002 |appointed = [[Rudolph Giuliani]] |predecessor = [[Jerome Hauer]] |successor = [[John T. Odermatt]] |birth_date = {{birth date|1946|10|12}} |death_date = {{death date|2012|01|19}} |birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]] |death_place = [[Beth Israel Medical Center]], [[Manhattan]], New York City }}
'''Richard James Sheirer''' (October 12, 1946 – January 19, 2012) was a [[public servant]] and [[New York City]] official. Sheirer served as the Director of the [[New York City Office of Emergency Management]] (O.E.M.) from February 2000 to March 2002.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|first=Bruce|last=Weber|title=Richard J. Sheirer, Official in Charge of Sept. 11 Rescues, Dies at 65 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/20/nyregion/richard-j-sheirer-official-in-charge-of-sept-11-rescues-dies-at-65.html?_r=2&hpw |work=[[New York Times]] |publisher=|date=2012-01-19 |accessdate=2012-02-04}}</ref> ==Life== Sheirer was born in Brooklyn on October 12, 1946, and raised in the borough's [[Canarsie]], [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn|Williamsburg]] and [[Flatbush, Brooklyn|Flatbush]] neighborhoods.<ref name=nytimes/> He graduated from [[St. Francis College]] in [[Brooklyn Heights]].<ref name=nytimes/>
Sheirer had begun his career as a [[dispatcher]] for the New York City Fire Department (NYFD) in 1967.<ref name=nytimes/> He was promoted to deputy commissioner under NYC Fire Commissioner [[Howard Safir]].<ref name=nytimes/> Safir, who became the [[New York City Police Commissioner]] in 1996, named Sheirer as his deputy commissioner for [[administration (government)|administration]] and [[chief of staff]].<ref name=nytimes/>
In February 2000, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani appointed Sheirer as Director of the OEM (Giuliani had created the department in 1996).<ref name=nytimes/> Sheirer was thrust into the public eye in September 2001, when, as director of the OEM during the [[September 11th attacks]], he became responsible for New York City's [[rescue and recovery effort after the September 11 attacks|rescue and recovery effort]].<ref name=nytimes/> Sheirer coordinated the rescue and clean-up efforts at the former [[World Trade Center site]], involving numerous federal, state, and local emergency agencies.<ref name=nytimes/> He stepped down as Director of the OEM in March 2002 when Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] took office.<ref name=nytimes/>
Sheirer died at [[Beth Israel Medical Center]] in [[Manhattan]] on January 19, 2012, from a heart attack he suffered in [[Staten Island]].<ref name=nytimes/> He was survived by his wife, Barbara Winston, and their five sons: Matthew, Joseph, Christopher, Andrew and Paul.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/9116779/Richard-Sheirer.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Richard Sheirer | date=March 1, 2012}}</ref>
On November 17, 2012 the City of New York renamed the segment of Laconia Avenue near Atlanic Avenue in [[Dongan Hills, Staten Island]] where Sheirer had resided to ''Commissioner Richard J. Sheirer Way''.<ref name=SIAdvance>{{cite news|first=Lore|last=Diane C.|title=Staten Island intersection renamed for former OEM Commissioner Richard Sheirer |url=http://www.silive.com/eastshore/index.ssf/2012/12/staten_island_intersection_ren.html |work=[[Staten Island Advance]] |publisher=|date=2012-12-02 |accessdate=2012-02-08}}</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
{{S-start}} {{S-gov}} {{s-bef|before=[[Jerome Hauer]]}} {{s-ttl|title=[[NYC Office of Emergency Management|Director, NYC Office of Emergency Management]]|years=2000-2002}} {{s-aft|after=John T. Odermatt}} {{S-end}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheirer, Richard}} [[Category:1946 births]] [[Category:2012 deaths]] [[Category:American Jews]] [[Category:New York City public officials]] [[Category:People associated with the September 11 attacks]] [[Category:New York City Fire Department]] [[Category:St. Francis College alumni]] [[Category:People from Brooklyn]] [[Category:People from Staten Island]] [[Category:People from Flatbush, Brooklyn]] [[Category:New York City Emergency Management]]

The '''sawing-off of [[Manhattan Island]]''' is an old [[New York City]] story that is largely unverified. It describes a [[practical joke]] allegedly perpetrated in 1824, by a retired ship carpenter named Lozier. According to the story, in the 1820s a rumor began circulating among city merchants that the weight of the urban district was causing southern [[Manhattan Island]] to sink, near the [[Battery Park City|Battery]]. It was believed that by cutting the island, towing it out, rotating it 180 degrees, and putting it back in place that Manhattan would be stabilized, and that the thin part of the island could be condemned. Surprisingly, the main concern was not the futility of the idea but of [[Long Island]]'s being in the way. Lozier finally assembled a large workforce and logistical support. At a massive groundbreaking ceremony, Lozier did not show up, but hid in [[Brooklyn]] and did not return for months.<ref name="1955newsarticle">{{cite news|author=[[Herbert Asbury|Asbury, Herbert]]|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LI0jAAAAIBAJ&sjid=eJkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6923,234788 |title=Sawing Off Of Manhattan|work=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]|location=Montreal|date= April 3, 1956}}</ref>

The story did not appear in any known [[newspaper]]s (although the press supposedly did not report on such pranks in that era) and no records have been found to confirm the existence of the individuals involved. This has led to speculation that the incident never occurred and the original report of the hoax was itself a hoax, which is the conclusion [[Joel Rose]] suggests in his book, ''New York Sawed in Half: An Urban Historical'' (2001).<ref>{{cite book|author=Rose, Joel|date=May 4, 2001 |publisher= Bloomsbury USA |title=New York Sawed in Half: An Urban Historical |isbn=9781582340982 }}</ref>  The hoax was first documented in [[Thomas F. De Voe]]'s (1811-1892) <ref name="market book">{{cite book|author=De Voe, Thomas F. De Voe |date=1862|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uow9AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA462#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Market Book|edition=full text online|pages= 462-64 }}</ref><ref name="devoe1">{{cite book|url=http://digital.lib.msu.edu/projects/cookbooks/html/authors/author_devoe.html |author=De Voe, Thomas Farrington|title=Feeding America|accessdate= October 14, 2010}}</ref> volume ''The Market Book'' (1862), as conveyed by his uncle who was Lozier's supposed associate, and was told again in [[Herbert Asbury]]'s work ''[[Herbert_Asbury#Bibliography|All Around The Town]]: Murder, Scandal, Riot and Mayhem in Old New York'' (1934, reissued as a Sequel to ''Gangs of New York''). Another condensed retelling occurs in the 1960s [[Reader's Digest]] book, ''[[Scoundrels and Scallywags]]: 51 Stories of the Most Fascinating Characters of Hoax and Fraud'' (1968).<ref>{{cite book|title=Scoundrels and Scallawags: 51 Stories of the Most Fascinating Characters of Hoax and Fraud|date=1968|publisher= The Reader's Digest Association |asin=B000H35TCY}}</ref><ref name="snopes">{{cite web|website=Snopes |url=http://www.snopes.com/history/hoaxes/sawingny.asp |date=February 10, 2006|accessdate=April 30, 2009|title=
I Saw New York}} (reviewing literature and concluding that original claimed event likely did not occur, and the story of the hoax is a hoax  itself)</ref><ref name="rose">{{cite book|author=Rose, Joel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8jXmbJRuPY4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=New York Sawed in Half: An Urban Historical|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]] |date=2001|isbn=1-58234-098-6}}</ref>

